WEBVTT

00:01.535 --> 00:02.769
(male narrator)
Last on "Perfect Strangers..."

00:02.803 --> 00:05.238
I now pronounce you
husband and wife.

00:09.442 --> 00:11.778
Well, right about now,
Balki and Mary Anne’s plane

00:11.812 --> 00:13.346
should be landing in Athens.

00:14.380 --> 00:16.683
Two hours on a small plane.

00:16.717 --> 00:18.418
Six more hours
in a fishing boat.

00:18.451 --> 00:21.588
Eleven‐mile hike,
and they’ll be at Balki’s house.

00:22.723 --> 00:25.191
It’s hard to believe
they’re finally married.

00:25.225 --> 00:26.793
It’s hard to believe
they’re finally married.

00:26.827 --> 00:30.096
It’s hard to believe tha‐that
we have the house to ourselves.

00:33.800 --> 00:35.335
You know what else
is hard to believe?

00:35.368 --> 00:37.137
What’s that?

00:37.170 --> 00:40.206
That in seven and a half months
you’re going to be a daddy.

00:41.474 --> 00:42.643
That’s nice.

00:47.347 --> 00:49.182
[theme song]

00:57.858 --> 01:01.528
♪ Sometimes the world
looks perfect ♪

01:01.562 --> 01:03.730
♪ Nothing to rearrange ♪

01:03.764 --> 01:06.800
♪ Sometimes you just
get a feeling ♪

01:06.833 --> 01:10.136
♪ Like you need
some kind of change ♪

01:11.371 --> 01:14.775
♪ No matter what
the odds are this time ♪

01:14.808 --> 01:17.377
♪ Nothings going to stand
in my way ♪

01:17.410 --> 01:18.879
♪ This flame in my heart ♪

01:18.912 --> 01:20.146
♪ Like a long lost friend ♪

01:20.180 --> 01:25.786
<i>♪ Gives every dark street</i>
<i>a light at the end ♪</i>

01:25.819 --> 01:28.622
♪ Standing tall ♪

01:28.655 --> 01:32.492
♪ On the wings of my dreams ♪

01:32.526 --> 01:35.562
♪ Rise and fall ♪

01:35.596 --> 01:39.499
♪ On the wings of my dreams ♪

01:39.533 --> 01:40.867
♪ The rain and thunder ♪

01:40.901 --> 01:42.503
♪ The wind and haze ♪

01:42.536 --> 01:45.839
♪ I’m bound for better days ♪

01:45.872 --> 01:49.242
♪ It’s my life and my dreams ♪

01:49.275 --> 01:52.679
♪ Nothing’s gonna stop me now ♪

02:03.790 --> 02:06.326
[instrumental music]

02:10.395 --> 02:12.498
Jennifer, honey?
You’d better hurry.

02:12.533 --> 02:14.568
Balki and Mary Anne
are going to be here any minute.

02:21.808 --> 02:23.644
Larry,
I’m seven months pregnant.

02:23.677 --> 02:24.845
I don’t hurry.

02:26.947 --> 02:28.582
Just, just take your time

02:28.615 --> 02:31.384
and park your pretty little
ankles right over here.

02:32.753 --> 02:33.854
My pretty little ankles?

02:33.887 --> 02:36.289
That’s all you think
is pretty about me anymore?

02:38.391 --> 02:40.426
Larry...

02:40.460 --> 02:42.428
You think I’m a whale.

02:44.430 --> 02:45.532
No! No! No!

02:45.566 --> 02:48.902
I‐I‐I don’t think
you’re a whale. I think tha...

02:48.935 --> 02:51.805
I‐I think you’re
beautiful, radiant

02:51.838 --> 02:53.640
and I love you very much.

02:53.674 --> 02:55.809
Hey, y‐y... I’ve got an idea.

02:55.842 --> 02:57.944
I’ll tell you what.

03:01.582 --> 03:05.652
Tonight, in, uh, instead
of having dinner at home, again

03:05.686 --> 03:06.820
when Balki and Mary Anne
get here

03:06.853 --> 03:08.822
why don’t we all
go out to dinner?

03:08.855 --> 03:10.557
I mean, we’ve got
a lot of catching up to do.

03:10.591 --> 03:14.294
Balki and Mary Anne have been
on Mypos for five months.

03:14.327 --> 03:17.330
I don’t wanna go out to dinner.
I don’t have anything to wear.

03:17.363 --> 03:20.801
Well, well, forget dinner.
Let’s all go to a movie.

03:20.834 --> 03:21.968
I don’t blame you, Larry

03:22.002 --> 03:24.270
for wanting to go
somewhere dark...

03:26.339 --> 03:29.209
...so no one sees you’re
married to the Goodyear Blimp.

03:31.444 --> 03:34.347
Well, well, no...
Honey, honey, that’s not true.

03:34.380 --> 03:37.417
Look, hey, hey...
I’ll tell you what.

03:37.450 --> 03:41.287
Let’s just forget
about Balki and Mary Anne.

03:41.321 --> 03:45.526
And, uh, why don’t we grab
a bottle of nonalcoholic wine

03:46.627 --> 03:51.932
go upstairs and...try
to rekindle that old passion.

03:52.699 --> 03:53.700
Hmm?

03:55.068 --> 03:57.370
Didn’t we just do that?

04:01.407 --> 04:03.376
Yeah. Yeah.

04:04.978 --> 04:07.380
Yeah, we just did that.

04:07.914 --> 04:09.616
We just did that about, uh

04:09.650 --> 04:13.486
seven weeks, four days
and eleven hours ago.

04:18.925 --> 04:21.461
Balki’s back
and he’s better than ever!

04:21.494 --> 04:23.564
Oh, cousin, cousin!

04:23.597 --> 04:26.967
Jennifer! Oh, Jennifer,
I’m so happy to be home!

04:27.000 --> 04:28.669
I missed everything
in this house.

04:28.702 --> 04:31.437
I missed running up the stairs!

04:31.471 --> 04:33.907
I missed running down
the stairs!

04:33.940 --> 04:35.709
I missed jumping over
this couch.

04:35.742 --> 04:36.877
Cousin.

04:36.910 --> 04:38.845
Cousin,
everything’s just the same.

04:38.879 --> 04:41.615
Still no upper lip.

04:41.648 --> 04:42.816
‐Except you, Jennifer.
‐Oh.

04:42.849 --> 04:46.486
‐You look beautiful.
‐Aw, thank you, Balki.

04:47.554 --> 04:50.991
Cousin, you exaggerated
in your letter.

04:51.024 --> 04:53.393
She’s nowhere
near as big as a house.

04:53.426 --> 04:54.828
What?

04:54.861 --> 04:57.330
Well, no, no.
E‐enough about us.

04:58.565 --> 05:02.402
‐Where’s Mary Anne?
‐She’s right outside.

05:02.435 --> 05:05.371
We, we have a surprise for you.

05:05.405 --> 05:08.408
‐Now, here we go. Here we go.
‐Mary Anne.

05:08.441 --> 05:10.544
‐Mary Anne.
‐Here we go.

05:13.847 --> 05:15.015
Hi!

05:19.485 --> 05:22.322
My little spud muffin
is having a tater tot.

05:24.725 --> 05:27.427
Well, that is great. Oh...

05:27.460 --> 05:30.463
[laughs]

05:32.065 --> 05:35.168
[both growling]

05:39.039 --> 05:40.541
‐Uh‐huh?
‐Uh‐huh.

05:40.574 --> 05:41.642
‐Uh‐huh?
‐Uh‐huh.

05:41.675 --> 05:43.777
[squealing]

05:45.546 --> 05:46.580
Here.

05:46.613 --> 05:47.914
Congratulations!

05:47.948 --> 05:50.551
Ooh, you’re just
like Larry’s drawing.

05:50.584 --> 05:51.785
Oh, no...

05:51.818 --> 05:54.487
Uh, why don’t we... Come on,
we’ll all sit down here.

05:54.521 --> 05:57.123
We’ve got a lot of,
of, uh, catching up to do.

05:57.157 --> 05:58.391
Here. Here you go, sweetheart.

05:58.424 --> 05:59.292
Take it easy, take it easy.

05:59.325 --> 06:00.493
You’ve got it.
You’re almost there.

06:00.527 --> 06:02.062
‐Almost there. Oh‐ho.
‐Pillow.

06:02.095 --> 06:03.997
Oh, here. Here.

06:04.030 --> 06:06.432
‐Can I help you, Mary Anne?
‐With what?

06:08.635 --> 06:09.736
Never mind.

06:09.770 --> 06:11.605
Well, this is perfect.

06:11.638 --> 06:14.107
You got here just in time
for my baby shower tomorrow

06:14.140 --> 06:16.076
so now it can be
for both of us.

06:16.109 --> 06:17.878
Oh, that’s sweet.

06:17.911 --> 06:19.513
Why don’t we show them
the new nursery?

06:19.546 --> 06:22.115
We put up new wallpaper.
I hope you like giraffes.

06:22.148 --> 06:23.517
Well, the meat’s a little tough

06:23.550 --> 06:25.418
but they’re a heck
of a lot of fun to ride.

06:29.055 --> 06:30.791
Larry, Larry.

06:30.824 --> 06:32.793
[instrumental music]

06:37.998 --> 06:39.499
There you go.

06:39.533 --> 06:42.035
A fan to keep your face cool.

06:42.068 --> 06:44.137
A blanket to keep
your body warm.

06:44.170 --> 06:45.906
A pillow for your aching back

06:45.939 --> 06:48.074
and some cozies
for your toesies.

06:50.076 --> 06:52.178
Is there anything else
I can do for you, honey?

06:52.813 --> 06:54.848
Yes. Shoot me.

06:58.785 --> 07:01.755
And, uh, how are you,
my little pork loin?

07:04.791 --> 07:05.792
I’m perfect.

07:05.826 --> 07:07.794
And don’t you forget it.

07:07.828 --> 07:10.531
[giggles]
Oh!

07:12.265 --> 07:13.767
Oh...

07:13.800 --> 07:17.504
You aren’t feeling
the least bit uncomfortable?

07:17.538 --> 07:18.204
No.

07:18.238 --> 07:19.806
‐Sore back?
‐No.

07:19.840 --> 07:21.542
‐Swollen ankles?
‐No.

07:21.575 --> 07:24.778
Wild, uncontrollable
almost murderous mood‐swings?

07:26.112 --> 07:28.649
Uh, I didn’t mean you, honey.

07:28.682 --> 07:30.684
Not you. Not you.

07:30.717 --> 07:33.987
So you aren’t experiencing
any symptoms of pregnancy?

07:34.020 --> 07:35.856
Well, just that pregnant glow.

07:36.890 --> 07:38.158
I hate you.

07:39.125 --> 07:40.160
(Balki)
’Don’t worry.’

07:40.193 --> 07:42.763
Because I have just the thing
to rid you of them

07:42.796 --> 07:44.731
pesky problems of pregnancy.

07:47.000 --> 07:48.201
What’s that?

07:50.003 --> 07:52.138
The Midolcrampabloatolous root.

07:56.242 --> 07:59.513
It helps you get rid of them
awful symptoms of pregnancy.

07:59.546 --> 08:02.248
I brought some home from Mypos
for Mary Anne, but

08:02.282 --> 08:04.951
she don’t need it.

08:04.985 --> 08:08.589
The Midolcrampabloatolous root?

08:10.557 --> 08:11.792
Yes.

08:11.825 --> 08:15.696
It’s grown in a special field
at the foot of Mount PMSocoulos.

08:22.603 --> 08:24.871
We, uh, tried planting
it closer to town

08:24.905 --> 08:27.808
but goats feeding in the area
kept exploding.

08:31.311 --> 08:34.246
‐Can I tempt you?
‐Thanks, but no.

08:34.280 --> 08:37.751
J‐J‐Jennifer’s right.
There‐there’s absolutely no way.

08:37.784 --> 08:40.787
Look, we don’t even know
if this root is safe.

08:40.821 --> 08:42.155
I mean, there’s,
there’s probably got some

08:42.188 --> 08:44.256
horrible side effects.

08:44.290 --> 08:45.959
Well, hmm, there, there is one

08:45.992 --> 08:48.929
but, I don’t... This is not
the place to discuss it.

08:48.962 --> 08:52.866
See? See? What happens?
What, does your hair turn green?

08:52.899 --> 08:53.900
What, your teeth get soft?

08:53.934 --> 08:56.036
‐What? What? What?
‐Well.

08:56.069 --> 09:00.741
It, it releases uncontrollable
passionate desires in a woman.

09:03.610 --> 09:05.746
Well, if it’ll help
reduce your swollen ankles...

09:08.882 --> 09:11.685
Larry, goats exploded.

09:11.718 --> 09:14.688
No, no, now, no conclusive
evidence has ever linked

09:14.721 --> 09:16.690
the goat explosions to the root.

09:16.723 --> 09:19.926
Do you hear that? You hear that?
"No conclusive evidence."

09:19.960 --> 09:21.995
Maybe you should try it.

09:22.028 --> 09:23.129
No, I‐I don’t want to.

09:23.163 --> 09:24.297
Okay, I’ll tell you what.
Alright.

09:24.330 --> 09:28.134
I’ll try it first,
and, and prove that it’s safe.

09:28.168 --> 09:30.003
Not only am I
not going to try it

09:30.036 --> 09:31.171
but you’re
not gonna try it either.

09:31.204 --> 09:35.275
What if you grow an arm
out of your neck or something?

09:35.308 --> 09:38.679
It’s time to read nursery rhymes
to our stomachs.

09:38.712 --> 09:41.381
I feel like "Goldilocks."
What do you feel like?

09:41.414 --> 09:42.949
(Jennifer)
"Humpty Dumpty."

09:51.157 --> 09:52.693
Excuse me. Excuse me.

09:53.860 --> 09:54.895
What are you doing?

09:54.928 --> 09:58.732
Balki, I’m doing this
for Jennifer’s own good.

09:58.765 --> 10:00.233
The sooner I take this
and show her that

10:00.266 --> 10:01.702
there is nothing wrong with it

10:01.735 --> 10:03.837
the sooner my life
returns to normal.

10:03.870 --> 10:07.708
Her life. Her life
returns to normal.

10:11.044 --> 10:12.913
Cut the babasticki.

10:16.149 --> 10:17.417
You’re not doing
this for Jennifer

10:17.450 --> 10:19.285
you’re doing it for yourself.

10:21.087 --> 10:22.989
‐You got me.
‐Well...

10:23.023 --> 10:25.826
Oh, give me that!
Give me that. Cousin...

10:32.298 --> 10:34.701
You can’t... You...

10:38.038 --> 10:41.842
You cannot just eat
the Midolcrampabloatolous root

10:41.875 --> 10:43.009
like that.

10:43.043 --> 10:44.077
What do you think this is?

10:44.110 --> 10:46.780
Some raw American
jicama crudite?

10:48.815 --> 10:50.316
You... This has to be prepared.

10:50.350 --> 10:51.852
You have to take
some shavings of this.

10:51.885 --> 10:53.987
Put them in the saucepan
with some bonemeal

10:54.020 --> 10:57.057
goat’s milk and a packet
of grape Kool‐Aid for color.

10:58.759 --> 11:00.861
Nothing is going to happen.

11:01.928 --> 11:03.997
Yeah, I knew it.

11:04.030 --> 11:07.300
Another bogus, Myposian...

11:07.333 --> 11:10.070
Oh, boy, I feel great!

11:12.272 --> 11:15.308
I feel alive! I feel tall!

11:15.341 --> 11:17.043
I feel a myriad of things!

11:17.077 --> 11:19.179
That’s a wonderful word,
isn’t it? Myriad?

11:19.212 --> 11:20.246
I wonder what it means.

11:20.280 --> 11:22.482
I have an Aunt Myriad.
No, that’s Aunt Miriam.

11:22.516 --> 11:23.950
Oh, I’ve got
to give her a call.

11:23.984 --> 11:25.318
You know Aunt Miriam?
Lovely woman.

11:25.351 --> 11:27.487
She has a mole on her back
the shape of Florida.

11:27.521 --> 11:28.922
Balki, have you ever noticed

11:28.955 --> 11:31.091
how many talk shows
there are now?

11:33.827 --> 11:36.096
You had to bite the root,
didn’t you?

11:37.898 --> 11:38.932
So?

11:38.965 --> 11:41.467
So, your eyes are bulging,
your hair is vibrating

11:41.502 --> 11:42.636
and you’re speaking
very quickly.

11:42.669 --> 11:43.737
Quickly? I didn’t notice
that I was talking quickly.

11:43.770 --> 11:44.771
But why would I notice
that I was talking quickly?

11:44.805 --> 11:46.973
It’s not like I’m timing
it with a stopwatch.

11:47.007 --> 11:49.209
My gym bag!
That’s where I left my watc
h!

11:49.242 --> 11:52.278
Balki, you have got to try this!

11:52.312 --> 11:54.347
No! No! No, I don’t want to!

11:54.380 --> 11:56.216
No! Ow! Ow!

11:56.249 --> 11:58.384
[mumbling]

12:07.293 --> 12:09.129
Nothing.

12:09.162 --> 12:11.397
Absolutely nothing.

12:11.431 --> 12:17.237
You know what I think?
Oooh‐woo! Ooh wah hah!

12:17.270 --> 12:20.941
Wow! Wow! Wow! Wow!

12:20.974 --> 12:22.342
This stuff is good!

12:22.375 --> 12:24.110
♪ Dai dai dai dai
dai dai dai dai ♪

12:24.144 --> 12:26.980
♪ Hey‐hey hey‐hey
hey‐hey hey‐hey ♪

12:33.554 --> 12:36.222
[instrumental music]

12:39.926 --> 12:42.796
I hope I get through
this shower. I am exhausted.

12:46.933 --> 12:49.035
I don’t know what Larry
and Balki were doing last night

12:49.069 --> 12:51.772
but they were making so much
noise it kept me up all night.

12:53.907 --> 12:56.877
[cackling]

13:04.184 --> 13:06.953
What have you two been up to
all night and half the morning?

13:06.987 --> 13:09.055
[laughter]

13:09.089 --> 13:11.391
‐Tell her! Tell her! Tell her!
‐Tell her! Tell her! Tell her!

13:11.424 --> 13:13.093
‐Tell her! Tell her!
‐Tell her! Tell her!

13:13.126 --> 13:14.861
‐Shut up!
‐Okay.

13:14.895 --> 13:16.462
We just thought we’d spruce up
the nursery for the shower.

13:16.496 --> 13:17.363
You know.

13:17.397 --> 13:20.200
Vacuuming, waxing,
dusting, dusting...

13:22.368 --> 13:23.937
And then we rewired the house.

13:23.970 --> 13:26.172
Giving us 30% more wattage.

13:26.206 --> 13:27.908
[screams]

13:27.941 --> 13:31.612
[cackling]

13:31.645 --> 13:34.114
Larry, you don’t know
how to rewire a house.

13:34.147 --> 13:36.550
That’s what I thought.
But it was a snap.

13:36.583 --> 13:37.784
‐First you reset the‐‐
‐Panels.

13:37.818 --> 13:39.953
Then you run feed from the main
switch into the circuit‐‐

13:39.986 --> 13:41.387
Breaker panels,
and into the junction‐‐

13:41.421 --> 13:42.956
‐Boxes. The tricky part‐‐
‐Was the‐‐

13:42.989 --> 13:44.024
‐Three way switches!
‐Three way switches!

13:44.057 --> 13:45.559
‐Do you remember those?
‐Oh! Oh!

13:45.592 --> 13:47.193
Oh! Oh! Oh! Oh! Oh!

13:47.227 --> 13:49.362
Three way! Three way! Three way!

13:49.395 --> 13:51.264
[mumbling]

13:52.899 --> 13:54.568
If you don’t remember,
the black‐‐

13:54.601 --> 13:55.636
Is positive and the white‐‐

13:55.669 --> 13:56.870
Is negative, then‐‐

13:56.903 --> 13:59.139
‐W‐wowww!
‐W‐wowww!

14:00.607 --> 14:03.109
Larry, why aren’t you blinking?

14:05.211 --> 14:06.479
Time waster!

14:06.513 --> 14:10.050
[laughter]

14:10.083 --> 14:12.252
Look, I don’t know what you guys
are up to, but I don’t have time

14:12.285 --> 14:14.988
to deal with this right now.
The guests are almost here.

14:15.021 --> 14:16.657
W‐why don’t you go and change?

14:16.690 --> 14:18.992
And we’d better hurry
and put out the food.

14:19.025 --> 14:20.994
Jennifer, do you ever
get a stabbing pain

14:21.027 --> 14:23.597
in your lower back that
shoots down through your legs?

14:23.630 --> 14:26.199
Yes. Yes! Do you get that too?

14:27.167 --> 14:28.201
No.

14:31.371 --> 14:34.307
[grunting]

15:03.637 --> 15:07.007
[grunting continues]

15:18.752 --> 15:21.054
Get me more of that root!

15:23.657 --> 15:25.258
‐This is all I have left.
‐That’s it?

15:25.291 --> 15:28.595
That’s all you’ve got?
We need more root!

15:28.629 --> 15:30.964
Don’t you have a root man
we could call?

15:31.598 --> 15:33.299
‐Unfortunately not.
‐Oh.

15:34.267 --> 15:35.969
But I have a better idea.

15:36.002 --> 15:38.471
After the baby shower,
we can fly to Mypos

15:38.505 --> 15:39.573
and get more root!

15:39.606 --> 15:40.641
Yes!

15:40.674 --> 15:42.342
We’ll fly to Mypos.

15:42.375 --> 15:44.310
‐Woo‐oo!
‐Woo‐oo!

15:44.344 --> 15:47.147
Bring back more root
and plant it in the backyard!

15:47.180 --> 15:50.951
Better yet, we’ll put
a giant grow light on the roof!

15:53.219 --> 15:55.288
‐Woo‐oo!
‐Woo‐oo!

15:56.523 --> 15:57.724
Wooo!

15:59.392 --> 16:00.527
Forget the roof!

16:00.561 --> 16:04.297
We’ll tear down the house
and plant root everywhere.

16:06.299 --> 16:09.235
I don’t know what we’ll
do with our clothes...

16:09.269 --> 16:11.404
...but we’ll worry
about that later.

16:12.305 --> 16:13.406
You know...

16:13.439 --> 16:15.241
It’s taken you six years,
cousin.

16:15.275 --> 16:18.411
But you have finally come up
with a plan that makes sense.

16:18.444 --> 16:19.479
‐Thank you!
‐No, thank you!

16:19.513 --> 16:20.514
‐No, thank you!
‐No, thank you!

16:20.547 --> 16:21.582
‐No, thank you!
‐No, thank you!

16:21.615 --> 16:23.483
[speaking gibberish]

16:24.651 --> 16:26.352
‐Woo! Ow!
‐Woo! Ow!

16:28.321 --> 16:30.290
Now give me the root!

16:36.663 --> 16:39.766
‐Oh, wow!
‐Oh, boy!

16:41.635 --> 16:43.770
Cousin, I have
the most brilliant idea.

16:43.804 --> 16:46.673
What if our knees
bent both ways?

16:46.707 --> 16:48.408
Come here! Come here. Come here.

16:48.441 --> 16:50.043
[mumbling]

16:50.076 --> 16:51.411
Alright, here. Hold it.

16:51.444 --> 16:53.413
[grunts]

17:08.194 --> 17:09.194
Ooh!

17:10.430 --> 17:12.365
[Larry muttering]

17:18.371 --> 17:21.575
(Jennifer)
Larry, what are you doing?

17:21.608 --> 17:24.310
We’re trying to see if we can
make my knees bend both ways.

17:24.344 --> 17:25.512
But thanks for asking.

17:28.481 --> 17:29.550
‐Mmm.
‐Mmm.

17:29.583 --> 17:31.484
[panting]

17:34.487 --> 17:36.222
[grunting]

17:37.624 --> 17:39.325
Why are you acting like this?

17:39.359 --> 17:42.295
[speaking gibberish]

17:45.766 --> 17:48.234
‐We ate the root.
‐We ate the root.

17:50.804 --> 17:53.740
And we didn’t
explode or anything.

17:53.774 --> 17:55.475
Jennifer,
you really gotta try it.

17:55.509 --> 17:57.210
Here, give me the root.
Give me the root.

17:57.243 --> 17:59.345
Oh, here, there’s
only a little bit left.

18:00.246 --> 18:02.616
But we want to give it to you.

18:02.649 --> 18:05.218
We’ll have a whole lot more
when we tear down the house.

18:05.251 --> 18:07.253
[giggling]

18:08.321 --> 18:09.823
What the hell
are you talking about?

18:09.856 --> 18:13.193
[speaking gibberish]

18:16.663 --> 18:17.798
‐The root.
‐The root.

18:19.099 --> 18:21.902
I don’t want any,
and I told you not to eat any.

18:21.935 --> 18:25.806
It’s making you weird.
Although you do seem taller.

18:33.514 --> 18:34.915
I’ll tell you what.

18:34.948 --> 18:36.249
Why don’t you two go outside

18:36.282 --> 18:38.819
and walk off
some of this energy, okay?

18:42.656 --> 18:44.490
‐Mmm...
‐Uh...

18:46.860 --> 18:50.430
‐Oh, bo‐y‐y!
‐Oh, w‐wow!

18:51.565 --> 18:52.866
You know, she’s right.

18:52.899 --> 18:55.168
‐Let’s take a walk!
‐Okay!

18:57.303 --> 18:59.272
[grunting]

19:02.576 --> 19:05.579
Balki! Why walk when we can eat?

19:05.612 --> 19:07.480
‐Woo... Food!
‐Food!

19:08.448 --> 19:10.383
[moaning]

19:13.854 --> 19:14.888
Wait, wait, wait.

19:14.921 --> 19:16.523
This food is for the party.

19:16.557 --> 19:18.925
Well, a nibble won’t hurt.
No one will notice.

19:18.959 --> 19:21.294
We’ll just have
a teensy meensy insy binsy

19:21.327 --> 19:23.664
little bite...of each dish.

19:23.697 --> 19:28.869
Okay, we’ll have a eensy teensy
weensy little bite of each dish.

19:30.871 --> 19:33.306
[giggling]

19:33.339 --> 19:35.308
[mumbling]

19:39.946 --> 19:43.283
[speaking gibberish]

19:47.487 --> 19:49.623
‐Very, very good!
‐Very, very good!

19:50.657 --> 19:53.627
[instrumental music]

20:05.606 --> 20:06.907
Hi, Jennifer.

20:09.442 --> 20:10.511
Hi, Mary Anne.

20:12.345 --> 20:14.447
‐Are you still mad at us?
‐Are you still mad at us?

20:16.517 --> 20:18.985
Because of you two,
instead of thank you cards

20:19.019 --> 20:21.522
we had to send out
apology cards.

20:23.790 --> 20:26.459
Well, if it makes you
feel any better

20:26.492 --> 20:29.462
Balki and I are paying
for our behavior.

20:29.830 --> 20:31.031
I know I am.

20:31.064 --> 20:34.735
I feel like the Myposian army
just marched across my face.

20:39.806 --> 20:42.643
Mary Anne, Mary Anne.

20:42.676 --> 20:44.745
I’m so sorry. I’m s...

20:44.778 --> 20:48.281
I never should have eaten
the Midolcrampabloatolous root.

20:49.983 --> 20:51.017
Forgive me?

20:51.051 --> 20:52.418
‐Okay!
‐Mm‐hmm.

20:52.919 --> 20:54.454
(Mary Anne)
Mmm.

20:55.922 --> 20:59.593
Jennifer, I’m so sorry.

20:59.626 --> 21:03.630
I never should’ve eaten
the Midolcrampabloatolous root.

21:04.330 --> 21:06.466
Will you forgive me?

21:10.403 --> 21:11.972
I don’t think so, Larry.

21:14.374 --> 21:17.077
But, but, Jen, I, I only ate it
so, so you could take it

21:17.110 --> 21:20.446
and, and get some relief
from your bloating, and...

21:20.480 --> 21:24.350
...aching and swelling
and whining.

21:26.452 --> 21:28.789
And, and, and I’m,
I’m not helping myself, am I?

21:28.822 --> 21:32.058
Cousin, you’re going down
in flames, but don’t worry.

21:32.092 --> 21:33.927
Because I have just the thing

21:33.960 --> 21:36.697
to get your relationship
back on track.

21:36.730 --> 21:40.934
Please, Balki, not another
bizarre Myposian remedy.

21:40.967 --> 21:43.604
Well, there’s nothing
bizarre about it.

21:43.637 --> 21:45.438
Here’s $20.

21:45.471 --> 21:48.609
Go to the movies,
sit in the balcony

21:48.642 --> 21:50.310
don’t watch the movie.

21:54.915 --> 21:56.517
What do you think, Jen?

21:56.550 --> 21:58.018
Sounds wonderful.

22:02.956 --> 22:04.925
Thanks, Balki,
that’s very kind of you.

22:04.958 --> 22:05.859
And that’s just the beginning.

22:05.892 --> 22:08.128
When you get home,
I’m going to whip you up

22:08.161 --> 22:10.597
a giant pig spleen float.

22:12.933 --> 22:15.468
With or without brine,
your choice.

22:28.048 --> 22:29.482
There, that’s better.

22:29.516 --> 22:30.551
‐Thank you.
‐No, thank you.

22:30.584 --> 22:31.585
‐No, thank you.
‐No, thank you.

22:31.618 --> 22:33.053
‐I am thanking you.
‐No, thank you, thank you.

22:33.086 --> 22:34.054
‐Thank you, thank you...
‐I am thanking you...

22:34.087 --> 22:36.957
‐Thank you, thank you...
‐Thank you, thank you...

22:36.990 --> 22:38.391
‐Oh.
‐Ow.

22:40.060 --> 22:42.629
[doorbell ringing]

22:42.663 --> 22:44.765
‐We’ll get it.
‐We’ll get it.

22:47.000 --> 22:48.401
(Jennifer)
’Larry.’

22:48.434 --> 22:49.636
Larry.

22:50.771 --> 22:51.538
Larry.

22:51.572 --> 22:53.540
‐They’re here!
‐They’re here!

22:54.608 --> 22:56.376
Oh, my God.

22:56.810 --> 22:58.745
[theme music]
